 @NahBNah  because traditionally the better gains you get are from overclocking your memory - this doesn't increase the power draw much (especially with an undervolt on the gpu, reduced my 3090 by 100W and increased memory by 25W for a total 75W net reduction) but the default thermals on the memory means you won't be able to overclock them as much, if at all, without modification (more efficient pads, putty, watercooling, etc.). although it could be possible the memory's sucking heat BACK from the heatsink off the GPU, so further testing with an undervolt is needed to see if that brings the temps down to represent this (if so, thermal pad modding will actually increase the memory's temperature, not reduce it, as it's able to more efficiently slurp up the heat from the heatsink).

ideally you never lower the power limit directly, unless you know your card's rockin some total bogus VRM Phase controllers or mosfets, something the 30 series was prone to (controllers with 0 safety measures cause they were from 2016 even though nvidia cards regularly ignore their own safety limits and spike at 200% power for up to 1.2 seconds, mosfets only rated for 40amp continous when they needed 50amp+ with that card's configuration). much better to do a manual undervolt which grants efficiency all along the curve and not JUST the max (e.g. at 50% utilisation you might get 20% more efficiency with an undervolt, as opposed to 0% with a power limit because it's not reaching that limit. like if you put your thumb over the mouth of a bottle, it'll only limit the water's flow once you've made the flow high enough that it touches your thumb)

tl;dr memory overclocks give massive gains but need thermal headroom, and power limiting is a safety measure not an efficiency one
